WEBVTT

00:03.500 --> 00:06.410
Just so you know, I had the
chicken tacos last night,

00:06.480 --> 00:09.550
and my stomach's doing somersaults.

00:09.650 --> 00:10.650
Uh...

00:10.680 --> 00:13.180
But our specials look good.

00:13.250 --> 00:14.920
We have tilapia,

00:14.950 --> 00:18.320
which is some kind of a
greasy white fish...

00:19.890 --> 00:22.560
... floating in cheese.

00:22.630 --> 00:24.940
Please don't make me
carry that out here.

00:26.730 --> 00:29.180
Now that you mention it,
that's exactly what I want.

00:30.270 --> 00:32.000
I'm gonna go exotic tonight, Beck.

00:32.070 --> 00:33.250
I'll have the pupusas.

00:33.270 --> 00:36.520
Take me away to El Salvador.

00:36.640 --> 00:37.910
Look, that's fried,

00:37.980 --> 00:40.410
and that's covered in some
kind of chunky sauce.

00:40.420 --> 00:42.280
I can't do that right now.

00:42.300 --> 00:44.010
Oh, um...

00:44.050 --> 00:45.700
You go first, Neil. I'm still looking.

00:45.740 --> 00:48.650
Okay. Uh, I would love
the three shrimp tacos.

00:48.750 --> 00:49.820
Pick something else.

00:49.850 --> 00:52.550
A lot of shrimp is peeled by Thai kids

00:52.560 --> 00:53.730
forced into slave labor,

00:53.740 --> 00:54.979
so you think you're eating scampi,

00:54.980 --> 00:56.500
but really you're exploiting children.

00:57.640 --> 01:00.459
I got an idea. What if I just
had one small shrimp taco,

01:00.460 --> 01:02.320
and I feel bad about it?

01:03.400 --> 01:04.720
Have the chile relleno.

01:04.739 --> 01:06.400
They're really good here. They're vegan.

01:06.470 --> 01:08.710
Yeah, I don't really like those.

01:08.810 --> 01:10.170
No, you will.

01:11.320 --> 01:13.010
Could you guys hurry up?

01:13.080 --> 01:15.780
I'm riding out this wave here.

01:15.850 --> 01:17.450
I'll have a shrimp burrito,

01:17.520 --> 01:20.150
and I'll have Neil's shrimp tacos.

01:20.220 --> 01:24.000
I don't know if it's those
Thai kids' sweat or tears,

01:24.020 --> 01:26.100
but they're delicious.

01:30.760 --> 01:33.680
Hey. I'm not buying this
food poisoning thing.

01:33.700 --> 01:34.930
I think you're hung over.

01:35.000 --> 01:36.670
I'm not hung over.

01:36.770 --> 01:38.000
Hold on.

01:38.070 --> 01:40.900
You're gonna have to eat
this way down there.

01:43.640 --> 01:45.780
You and I are going
to a meeting tonight.

01:47.210 --> 01:48.940
So, Neil, what do you do for a living?

01:48.960 --> 01:50.310
Uh, I'm a preschool teacher.

01:50.420 --> 01:51.610
Preschool, huh?

01:51.720 --> 01:53.630
What's that, like, playing
with blocks and stuff?

01:53.650 --> 01:55.549
Blocks and stuff?

01:55.550 --> 01:58.350
Dan, they are so far beyond that now.

01:58.460 --> 02:00.960
Oh, no, actually, no, blocks
are a big part of it.

02:01.330 --> 02:03.790
Oh, well, the old ways
are still the best ways.

02:05.160 --> 02:07.540
We try to inspire the
children's imagination

02:07.550 --> 02:11.340
with nonspecific, gender-neutral,
tactile objects.

02:11.720 --> 02:14.500
Why would you do that when there's TV?

02:17.260 --> 02:19.810
Excuse me. I just gotta go tinkle.

02:19.850 --> 02:21.260
Sorry. It's a work term.

02:25.020 --> 02:26.340
- He's great, right?
- Yeah.

02:26.360 --> 02:28.050
Does he remind you of anybody?

02:30.220 --> 02:31.860
Not really. Here's a clue,

02:31.880 --> 02:33.490
because I want you to figure it out.

02:33.500 --> 02:35.360
David!

02:37.620 --> 02:38.680
What?

02:40.100 --> 02:41.799
No... No way.

02:41.800 --> 02:43.570
Two entirely different people.

02:43.600 --> 02:45.560
Wait, wait. That wasn't David?

02:45.570 --> 02:47.100
No!

02:47.120 --> 02:48.770
She's controlling Neil

02:48.800 --> 02:52.040
the same way she controlled David.

02:52.050 --> 02:54.480
He has the same jumpy,
scared eyes as David.

02:54.500 --> 02:55.950
Are you sure that wasn't David?

02:58.220 --> 02:59.660
Hey, sorry we're late.

02:59.700 --> 03:01.759
I had to get Harris to
watch Mary and Mark.

03:01.760 --> 03:04.190
We had to lie and tell her
she'd get money for it.

03:04.260 --> 03:05.840
That's gonna be a fight later.

03:07.360 --> 03:08.390
Sorry.

03:08.460 --> 03:10.220
Oh, Neil, this is my brother, D.J.,

03:10.260 --> 03:11.340
- and his wife, Geena.
- Oh, hey.

03:11.360 --> 03:12.400
- Hi.
- Hi.

03:12.450 --> 03:14.010
We were just talking
about whether people

03:14.030 --> 03:16.630
tend to date the same
types over and over.

03:16.650 --> 03:18.740
- What do you think?
- Oh, pbht, absolutely.

03:18.800 --> 03:20.116
For... For example, I used to have

03:20.140 --> 03:22.640
a horribly self-destructive
thing for dominant women.

03:22.740 --> 03:24.770
They... Ugh.

03:24.800 --> 03:27.080
They'd push me around,
and I'd feel awful.

03:27.100 --> 03:29.050
But I... I got over that.

03:30.450 --> 03:32.580
By the way, I... I
really need to apologize

03:32.650 --> 03:34.380
for that whole shrimp thing. I...

03:35.350 --> 03:36.800
I don't know who that guy was.

03:38.500 --> 03:40.900
Oh, I think we all know who that was.

